7 Section 2. Section 37-3-401, MCA, is amended to read:
8 "37-3-401. Report of incompetence or unprofessional conduct. (1) Notwithstanding EXCEPT AS
9 PROVIDED IN [SECTION 1], NOTWITHSTANDING any provision of state law dealing with confidentiality, each licensed
10 physician, professional standards review organization, and the Montana medical association or any component
11 society of the association shall and any other person may report to the board any information that the physician,
12 organization, association, society, or person has that appears to show that a physician is:
13 (a) medically incompetent;
14 (b) mentally or physically unable to safely engage in the practice of medicine; or
15 (c) guilty of unprofessional conduct.
16 (2) (a) Information that relates to possible physical or mental impairment connected to habitual
17 intemperance or excessive use of addictive drugs, alcohol, or any other drug or substance by a licensee or to
18 other mental or chronic physical illness of a licensee may be reported to the appropriate personnel of the
19 medical assistance program established by the board under 37-3-203, in lieu of reporting directly to the board.
20 (b) The medical assistance program personnel referred to in subsection (2)(a) shall report to the
21 board the identity of a licensee and all facts and documentation in their possession if:
22 (i) the licensee fails or refuses to:
23 (A) comply with a reasonable request that the licensee undergo a mental, physical, or chemical
24 dependency evaluation or a combination of evaluations;
25 (B) undergo a reasonable course of recommended treatment, including reasonable aftercare;
26 (C) satisfactorily complete a reasonable evaluation, a course of treatment, or aftercare;
27 (ii) the licensee's condition creates a risk of harm to the licensee, a patient, or others; or
28 (iii) the medical assistance program personnel are in possession of information that appears to
